\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs32\b1 1}{\f0\fs24  (21:8\endash 11) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Conflict, Cause\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Strife\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Ishmael\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Sarah\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Isaac\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Feast, Weaning}{\f0\fs24 : there was the cause of the conflict. Very simply, sin caused the conflict within Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s family, and sin is usually the cause of conflict among most of us. What happened in Abraham\u8217\'92s family was this: Abraham threw a }{\f0\fs24\i1 great feast}{\f0\fs24  for Isaac when he was weaned from his mother\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s breast. Note the word }{\f0\fs24\i1 great}{\f0\fs24 : it was a great feast. This was apparently a Near East custom of that day when a child reached 2\endash 3 years old. At some point during the feast, Sarah saw Ishmael mocking Isaac: ridiculing, poking fun, being mean-spirited and bitter toward him. Remember, Isaac was just a baby, two or three years old, and Ishmael was sixteen or seventeen years old (see Ge. 16:16; 21:5). Just imagine a young man that old mocking and ridiculing a baby. Moreover, note the word }{\f0\fs24\i1 mocking}{\f0\fs24  (metsachcheq). The Hebrew has the idea of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93always mocking.\u8221\'94 Ishmael always displayed bitterness and anger toward Isaac; he was always mocking and being mean-spirited to the baby. Why? What would cause Ishmael to be so mean to Isaac? Because Abraham was always }{\f0\fs24\i1 heaping attention}{\f0\fs24  upon Isaac, the attention that Ishmael had once received before Isaac\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s birth. Abraham\u8217\'92s attention was now split two ways, and he was more focused upon the baby, Isaac, than upon Ishmael. Ishmael should have understood: he was old enough to know that the baby was bound to become the focus of attention. He was old enough to understand \u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab that the baby needed more attention}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab that the baby was bound to be a special joy to Abraham because he was born in Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s old age}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab that the baby was the promised child, miraculously given by God}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 But Ishmael refused to accept the baby\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s presence within the family, refused to accept Isaac as }{\f0\fs24\i1 the promised child}{\f0\fs24 . He continuously mocked, adopting a mean-spirited attitude toward the child who was appointed by God to be }{\f0\fs24\i1 the promised son}{\f0\fs24 . And Sarah saw the mockery time and again. Apparently, the ridicule reached a peak at the great feast celebrating Isaac\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s weaning, and Sarah witnessed the ugly scene. It was all she could take, enough was enough, and she boiled over. She demanded that Abraham send away (cast out, drive out, get rid of) the slavewoman and her son, Ishmael.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Ishmael had sinned through his mockery and jealousy and his failure to trust the will and care of God. Now Sarah was sinning by over-reacting. She was demanding a cruel solution to the conflict. She took matters into her own hands instead of seeking God for an answer to the conflict. She was overtaken by a spirit of distrust toward God and of cruelty toward Ishmael and his mother, Hagar. Remember, Hagar had been Sarah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s personal servant for decades. But Sarah was apparently so overtaken with anger that she just ignored God and reacted against Ishmael and Hagar. The effect upon Abraham was devastating, for he loved Ishmael, loved him with all his heart. Abraham was stricken with a heavy heart; he was distressed, not knowing what to do.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . Note two facts about conflict and strife:}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 (1)\tab Conflict is very dangerous.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge21.8-11&off=0&ctx=eternal+inheritance%0a~1+(21:8%E2%80%9311)+Conflict"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 121). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs32\b1 2}{\f0\fs24  (21:12\endash 13) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Conflict, Answer to}{\f0\fs24 : there was the answer to the conflict. The answer was God. Being forced to send a child away is almost more than any loving parent can bear. Sarah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s demand to get rid of Ishmael was a heavy pressure upon Abraham. But God knew. He knew all about Abraham\u8217\'92s heavy heart and distress, all about his perplexity, just not knowing what to do. No doubt, Abraham prayed and discussed the matter with God, and God heard and cared about Abraham\u8217\'92s need. Therefore, God set about to meet Abraham\u8217\'92s need.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. First, God gave Abraham His Word. God spoke to Abraham, encouraging him and relieving the distress and grief. Note when God spoke to Abraham: at night (v. 14). Apparently, Abraham was doing what we all do when we are under heavy distress: pray. He was either lying in bed or up during the night, praying and thinking the conflict through. And God met him: the Word of God came to Abraham and met his need.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 As for Sarah, she was right. Ishmael needed to be sent away, for his mocking and ridicule was too imbedded in him to change. The conflict would only grow worse. But Sarah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s attitude of cruelty toward Ishmael was wrong, and her failure to seek and trust God for an answer was wrong. She had broken Abraham\u8217\'92s heart and caused heavy distress and grief for him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 But as noted, God spoke to Abraham, and God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Word always meets the need of the human heart. God\u8217\'92s Word always relieves our distress and grief, relieves whatever conflict wages within our souls. God\u8217\'92s Word always encourages us: it encouraged Abraham and it encourages us.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 b. Second, God reminded Abraham of His great purpose: Isaac was to be the promised son, the son who was to give rise to the chosen line, the offspring of God. Remember, this refers both to the people of God, those who truly believe and follow after God, and to the promised Savior, the Lord Jesus Christ. Ishmael was not the line chosen to bring God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Seed, the Savior, into the world; Isaac was (see Ga. 3:16).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 c. Third, God assured Abraham that the conflict would be resolved. Ishmael would be looked after and richly blessed by God. He would grow into a great nation of people. God would see to it. Note why: not for Ishmael\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s sake but for Abraham\u8217\'92s sake. Ishmael\u8217\'92s egotistical, superior attitude over Isaac had apparently become imbedded and extremely sinful. Consequently, God could not act for Ishmael\u8217\'92s sake; God could not sanction Ishmael\u8217\'92s sinful ways by acting in his behalf. But Abraham was a different matter. Abraham loved and followed God; therefore, for Abraham\u8217\'92s sake, God would bless Abraham\u8217\'92s son Ishmael.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 The point is this: God knew all about the conflict, all of Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s distress and perplexity, that he did not know what to do, that he did not know how to handle the conflict. Therefore, God met Abraham. Most likely, Abraham was in prayer, crying out for God to help him. And God did.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab God gave Abraham His Word: spoke to Abraham, relieving his distress and telling him what to do (v. 12).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab God reminded Abraham of God\u8217\'92s great purpose (v. 12).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab God assured Abraham that the conflict would be resolved: God would take care of Ishmael and bless him (v. 13).}
\par\pard\plain \li1080\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s answer to conflict is the same for every generation, for every one of us. No matter what the conflict is \u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab the answer is found in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Word. His Word will relieve whatever distress we have and give us the answer to our questions. God\u8217\'92s Word tells us what to do. Our task is to search His Word for the peace we need and for the answers to our questions}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab the answer is found in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s purpose. We must remind ourselves of God\u8217\'92s purpose both for His people and for the world}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab the answer is found in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s assurance of blessing. No matter what the solution to the conflict may be, God will take care of us and our needs\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 if we will trust and believe God, just as Abraham did\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge21.12-13&off=0&ctx=o+harm%E2%80%9D+(Pr.+3:30).%0a~2+(21:12%E2%80%9313)+Conflic"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, pp. 121\endash 122). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
