\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs32\b1 4}{\f0\fs24  (21:16}{\f0\fs24\super c}{\f0\fs24 \endash 21) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Conflict, Conquest of\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Ishmael}{\f0\fs24 : there was the conquest or triumph over the conflict. Seven things now happened that clearly show us how to conquer and triumph over conflict.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. Hagar wept bitterly and lifted up her voice in prayer. To }{\f0\fs24\i1 lift up one\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s voice}{\f0\fs24  suggests prayer. Hagar and Ishmael would soon die, all because of the conflict that raged within the soul of Ishmael. Hagar had reached the end of her strength, done all she could. She simply could do no more, not within her own strength. Sitting there, she wept bitterly and did the only thing she could do: lifted up her voice and cried out to God in prayer.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . Too often, this is the position we have to be in before we will cry out to God: at the end of our rope, no strength, no way to do anything within ourselves.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Nevertheless, God loves us and cares for us. We must, therefore, cry out to God, whether early or late, whether facing mild or desperate need.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 b. Hagar listened to the Word of God and thought over her problem (v. 17}{\f0\fs24\super a}{\f0\fs24 ). God heard Hagar\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s prayer and spoke to her out of heaven. God gave Hagar }{\f0\fs24\i1 His Word}{\f0\fs24  to meet her need. Note what God did:}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He stirred her to think about her problem. \u8220\'93What is the problem, Hagar?\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . We have the permanent Word of God. When we face problems and crises, we desperately need to go to God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Word for guidance, crying out to Him for help and direction. Note also, we need to do what God was stirring Hagar to do: think through the problem facing us. If we sincerely seek God in prayer and in His Word, thinking through the problem to the best of our ability, God will help us. We will be able to conquer and triumph over all conflicts, problems, and crises.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 c. Ishmael lifted up his voice and cried out to God, apparently asking for forgiveness (v. 17}{\f0\fs24\super c}{\f0\fs24 ). Again, }{\f0\fs24\i1 lifting up one\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s voice}{\f0\fs24  suggests prayer. Note, God said twice that He had heard the voice of Ishmael. Apparently Ishmael was also praying, weeping, and crying out to God. Most likely, he was asking God for forgiveness, knowing that it was his mocking and ridicule that had brought him and his mother to the point of death.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . God stresses the fact that He heard }{\f0\fs24\i1 the voice}{\f0\fs24  (Hebrew) of Ishmael. God says this two times. This points out the utter necessity of repentance, of crying out for God to forgive our sins when we have done wrong. Then and only then does God hear us.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge21.16c-21&off=0&ctx=ssion%E2%80%9D+(Pr.+29:22).%0a~4+(21:16%EF%BB%BFc%E2%80%9321)+Confl"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 123). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
